title: For Sale:  Remington Model 81  (300 savage)
location: North Branch (can meet in Twin Cities), Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Dad passed away and I'm selling his guns.  This one is a Remington model 81 semi-automatic.  It is the 300 savage caliber model made probably near 1947.  These guns were used by the police for a while and a lot of deer have been killed with them.  The 300 savage is a good mid-range caliber for most woods hunting.

It has a side mounted scope which is mounted properly so it doesn't interfere with the shell ejection.  You can easily drop down to the "iron sights".  Very handy when you bump the scope in the field and don't know if you knocked it out of sight.  That feature saved me from losing a deer one year on my Win Model 94 when my son bumped it off the tailgate of the truck.  When we sighted it in a few days later it was off by about 3 feet at 100 yards.  Good thing I used the iron sights to drop my buck that year!!!

Here is a web page dedicated to the model 8 and 81 with some interesting facts about this rifle:

http://thegreatmodel8.remingtonsociety.com/?page_id=8

title: For Sale:  New Crimson Trace Laser for a S&W M&P
postcontent:
I recently purchased a new M&P 9 Compact that came bundled with the crimson trace grip. I have put about 400 rounds through the gun so far and have only used the laser itself a handful of times. 

It has been barely used, no scratches on it, and battery life is full. 

My Observations:

The grip itself is comparable to the -Large- back strap that comes with the gun itself.  If you have small hands, and use the small back strap, then the crimson trace might not be for you. I have smaller hands, and personally, I feel the difference between the small and large back strap changes the dynamics of my grip enough that I would prefer to forgo the laser grip and just use the small back strap.

That is why I am selling it, so keep what I said about your hand size in mind before you decide to buy. I don't want anyone to be surprised with what they are buying.

As far as the C  Trace grip itself, it is for a M&P -COMPACT- models only. 9mm, .357 , or .40. It also does not fit the models with ambidextrous safety.

The MSRP on crimsontrace.com is 329. With a quick google search I found cheapest on Amazon  and some other online sites was about 285-295 without shipping.

I'm asking 225, because it has barely been used and I believe 225 is  more than fair price.

location: Southeast Wake County, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: Very nice Spanish Mauser FR-8 in .308 caliber! These guns were reworked from M.1943 Mauser rifles, and this one is accordingly stamped on the receiver, "Fabrica De Armas La Coruna 1955". The receiver displays a slightly fading Spanish crest. FR-8 was used for practice by Spanish soldiers before they were issued CETME assault rifles. The rifle has a fake gas tube installed under the barrel, to make it look like the CETME rifle. This fake gas tube is actually a cleaning kit container (the cleaning kit is not included). This gun has stronger, 1898-type action than FR-7, which was build on 1893-type action. Straight bolt handle. Stock with pistol grip. The stock does not display any markings. All matching serial numbers (the matching serial numbers are stamped on the receiver, barrel and on the bolt only; all the remaining parts do not display any numbers, which is correct for this model). CONDITION: Excellent, as rebuilt by Spanish arsenal. Most of phosphate finish is still on metal. Very nice stock has been filled in one place. Excellent bore with strong and shiny rifling. Strong action. All the internal parts of the rifle are in excellent condition, with little visible wear. Mechanically, the rifle is in great condition.
